---
import BaseLayout from '@/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About"
  description="The thesis behind From Idea to Customer — why ownership is a practice, not a privilege."
>
  <div class="max-w-2xl">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-6">About</h1>

    <div class="prose prose-gray">
      <h2>The core thesis</h2>
      <p>
        There is no reason a junior person with no prior experience can't start thinking like a
        CTO on day one. Not <em>being</em> a CTO — thinking like one. The difference between
        junior and CTO isn't the mindset. It's the number of squares and the complexity of the
        trade-offs. The muscle is the same.
      </p>
      <p>
        This curriculum doesn't teach people how to build an application from scratch.
        Everybody and their uncle is doing that. This curriculum teaches people how to
        <em>think</em> — how to see problems through different lenses, how to own outcomes
        rather than follow checklists, and how to operate across the functions of a SaaS
        business with the awareness and judgment that typically takes a decade to develop.
      </p>

      <h2>The Checkerboard</h2>
      <p>
        The board is the field — the full landscape of everything that needs to be managed
        across a SaaS business. Each square is a unit of responsibility. A junior person gets
        one square. Own it completely. An intermediate person gets more. A senior person gets
        even more — and their job includes ensuring other people own their squares well.
      </p>
      <p>
        The critical insight: while technical skills may take years to develop, the skill of
        owning a square can be observed and learned in months. The discipline is the same
        whether you own one square or fifty.
      </p>

      <h2>The Conference Room</h2>
      <p>
        The learning mechanism is drawn from direct experience leading teams. After working on
        something, the learner explains what they worked on — not reciting from a checklist,
        but explaining it clearly enough that someone from a completely different department
        could understand it.
      </p>
      <p>
        You cannot explain something clearly if you don't understand it. The moment you can't
        just read back the steps, you have to go deeper than the steps. You have to build a
        mental model of the system, the purpose, the context. That's where ownership starts.
      </p>

      <h2>The SaaS domain</h2>
      <p>
        The curriculum is grounded in the SaaS business model across two stages: early-stage
        startup and late-stage startup. The startup-to-late-stage arc introduces a natural
        tension that becomes a teaching tool: early-stage, one person wears five hats. Late-stage,
        hats become dedicated roles. The skill shifts from "do everything" to "know enough to
        lead people who do it better than you."
      </p>

      <h2>The codebase</h2>
      <p>
        This site is built on the principle that onboarding is a core leadership competency,
        not an afterthought. Every architectural decision is documented and explainable. The
        codebase itself is a teaching artifact: raw SQL so every query is visible, Astro for
        content-first structure, a migration runner you can read in fifty lines. No magic.
        No ORMs hiding the queries. Every layer is visible and explainable to a junior engineer
        on their first day.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
